    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a great point; a generic email can feel like a cold rejection, especially for a senior candidate who clearly impressed you. Let's inject some specific warmth about their technical performance while keeping the \"no\" firm and professional.\n\nHere is a revised draft that acknowledges their specific strength in the technical round, perhaps even using a small metaphor about how their code (or problem-solving) stood out, before gently closing the door.\n\n***\n\n**Subject:** Update Regarding Your Application for Senior Developer Role\n\nHi [Candidate Name],\n\nThank you again for the time you spent with our team for the Senior Developer position in Austin. We truly enjoyed our conversation and were genuinely impressed by your performance, particularly during the technical assessment.\n\nYour ability to dissect complex problems and write clean, efficient code was evident and stood out significantly against the other finalists. It was a rare find to see that level of depth in a candidate at this stage.\n\nHowever, after careful consideration, we have decided to move forward with another candidate whose specific experience aligns slightly more closely with our immediate project roadmap. This was a difficult call, as we were thrilled by your potential and the quality of your technical skills.\n\nWe sincerely appreciate your interest in [Company Name] and",
